GIT:  (version control)
  Git is a tool, save and , manage different version of your files and code.

version control means track changes, recover previous saved code.

Git Config: 
  git config : git know who you are, like set username or email 

  1.System level → affects all users on this computer.
  2.Global level → affects only your user.
  3.Local level → affects only the current repository.

Listing all: git config --list --show-origin

System Level:
sudo: (super-user do)
1. create system level settings: (file created)
    sudo touch /etc/gitconfig   
2. Add a system-level username and email
    sudo git config --system user.name "System User"
    sudo git config --system user.email "system@example.com"
3. Verify system-level config
    git config --system --list

Global Level:
Step 1: Set your global user
    git config --global user.name "akash"
    git config --global user.email "personal@example.com"
Step 2: Verify global config
    git config --global --list
If you want to edit then use "git config --global --edit"

Local Level:
(Repo)
1. git init    --> Initalize the Repo.
2. git add .
3. git commit -m "commited"
4. git log --oneline
5. git show --name-only <commit-hash>   --> show file names after commited
6. git show <commit-hash> -- file1.txt  --> this is revert by (read only)
7. git checkout <commit-hash> -- file1.txt --> this will be revert (write) 







